@page "/"

<!-- ========================= -->
<!-- HERO SECTION -->
<!-- ========================= -->
<section class="hero">
    <div class="hero-content">
        <h1>RIPPLE: Growing Food. Growing Community.</h1>
        <p>
            Fresh, sustainable food shouldn’t depend on your ZIP code. Ripple is building a year‑round 
            aquaponics facility in Chicagoland to bring healthy produce and fish directly to communities 
            facing food insecurity — all through clean, efficient, climate‑resilient farming.
        </p>

        <div class="hero-buttons">
            <a href="/about" class="btn primary">Learn More</a>
            <a href="/get-involved" class="btn secondary">Get Involved</a>
            <a href="/donate" class="btn donate">Donate</a>
        </div>
    </div>
</section>

<!-- ========================= -->
<!-- PROBLEM SECTION -->
<!-- ========================= -->
<section class="problem">
    <h2>The Challenge</h2>
    <p>
        More than one‑third of Chicago‑area households struggle to afford basic living costs, putting them 
        at serious risk of hunger. Many neighborhoods are food deserts, where access to fresh produce is 
        limited or nonexistent. Families deserve better — and sustainable solutions can help close the gap.
    </p>
</section>

<!-- ========================= -->
<!-- HOW RIPPLE WORKS -->
<!-- ========================= -->
<section class="how-it-works">
    <h2>How Ripple Works</h2>

    <div class="steps">
        <div class="step">
            <h3>1. We raise fish.</h3>
            <p>Nile tilapia produce nutrient‑rich waste that becomes the foundation of our growing system.</p>
        </div>

        <div class="step">
            <h3>2. We grow plants.</h3>
            <p>Buttercrisp lettuce and other leafy greens thrive in this natural, soil‑free environment.</p>
        </div>

        <div class="step">
            <h3>3. We feed the community.</h3>
            <p>
                Our produce and fish are distributed locally through food pantries and community partners.
                Aquaponics uses up to <strong>90% less water</strong> than traditional farming and produces 
                fresh food <strong>year‑round</strong>.
            </p>
        </div>
    </div>
</section>

<!-- ========================= -->
<!-- WHY AQUAPONICS -->
<!-- ========================= -->
<section class="why-aquaponics">
    <h2>Why Aquaponics?</h2>
    <p>
        Aquaponics is a closed‑loop system that recycles water, conserves resources, and produces 
        nutrient‑dense food at high efficiency. It’s sustainable, scalable, and ideal for urban environments 
        where land and fresh food access are limited.
    </p>

    <ul class="benefits">
        <li>Operates year‑round</li>
        <li>Uses significantly less water and land</li>
        <li>Reduces reliance on long‑distance supply chains</li>
        <li>Provides predictable, high‑quality harvests</li>
        <li>Supports community health and education</li>
    </ul>
</section>

<!-- ========================= -->
<!-- OUR MISSION -->
<!-- ========================= -->
<section class="mission">
    <h2>Our Mission</h2>
    <p>
        Ripple exists to address food insecurity through sustainable, community‑centered aquaponics. 
        We aim to increase access to fresh food, support local distribution networks, provide education 
        and volunteer opportunities, and build a model that other communities can replicate.
    </p>
</section>

<!-- ========================= -->
<!-- COMMUNITY FIRST -->
<!-- ========================= -->
<section class="community">
    <h2>Community First</h2>
    <p>
        Ripple is more than a facility — it’s a community project. Volunteers help with planting, harvesting, 
        packaging, and outreach. Local students and researchers contribute to innovation. Neighborhood partners 
        help distribute food where it’s needed most.
    </p>

    <a href="/get-involved" class="btn primary">Get Involved</a>
</section>

